  "prompt": "Did anybody ever document what the Dodo bird of Mauritius tasted like?",
  "response": "Yes, there are historical accounts that describe the taste of the dodo bird. The dodo, a flightless bird native to Mauritius, was reported to have a flavor that some contemporary sources likened to a mix between turkey and a type of game bird, though specific descriptions of its taste can be somewhat subjective and varied. \n\nThe earliest documentation of the dodo's taste comes from sailors and explorers who encountered the bird in the late 16th and early 17th centuries. One of the most notable accounts is from Manuel de Orellana, a Portuguese explorer, who described the dodo as having a taste that was enjoyable and savory. However, since the dodo became extinct in the late 17th century, there are no modern accounts of its taste, and the descriptions are based solely on historical observations.",
